In [6]:
# Treating the outliers using the Capping method.

for i in df.columns[1:-1]:
    if df[i].dtype!='object':
        q1 = df[i].quantile(0.25)
        q3 = df[i].quantile(0.75)
        IQR=q3-q1
    
        lower = q1-1.5*IQR
        upper = q3+1.5*IQR
        df[i]=np.where(df[i]>upper,upper,np.where(df[i]<lower,lower,df[i]))

Here, Capping method is used instead of removing the outliers so that the data is not lost. In capping method, outlier values are replaced either with the upper limit or with the lower limit of the Interquartile range(IQR).¶

In [9]:
# Filling the null values

for i in df.columns:
    if df[i].dtype=='object':
        df[i].fillna(df[i].mode()[0],inplace=True)  # Filling the Null values in categorical columns using mode value.
    elif df[i].dtype!='object':
        df[i].fillna(df[i].mean(),inplace=True)    # Filling the null values in numeric columns using mean value.
    else:
        print('Error')

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)¶

plt.figure(figsize=(5,3))

Silver      8572
Tin         6487
Gold        6324
Platinum     840
Name: LoyalClass, dtype: int64

Observation¶

  • Silver class has the highest number of customers, that is 38.57 % of total customers , whereas Platinum class has the lowest (3.77 %).
  • Tin and Gold class collectively represents 57.64 % of the total customers and they do not have much difference in customer participation.
In [11]:
# Relationship between average amount spent by each class using a pie chart

explode = (0.05,0.05,0.05,0.05)
df.groupby('LoyalClass').mean().plot(kind='pie',y='LoyalSpend',autopct='%1.0f%%',explode=explode,legend=False)
plt.axis('off')
plt.show()

Observation¶

  • Even though Platinum class has only 3.77 % participation of customers, its contribution in total loyalty spent amount is 59 %, that means customer in Platinum card belong to the higher income group and they are more likely to buy the product of the company.

  • Similarly, the Silver and Tin class have the customer participation rate of 38.57 % and 29.19 % respectively, but their contribution in total the amount spent is only 8 % and nearly 0% respectively, that means customers in this class are likely to belong to the lower income group and they are less likely to buy the product.

  • Customers in Gold class belong to the middle income group and they are also likely to buy the product.

# Analysis of correlation between numeric features using heatmap

plt.figure(figsize=(6,6))
sns.heatmap(df.corr(numeric_only=True),annot=True,cmap='viridis')
plt.title('Correlation analysis between the features')
plt.yticks(rotation=0)
plt.show()

Observation¶

  • Demographic affluence and TargetBuy have a strong positive correlation with each other (0.72), that means a customer with higher demographic affluent value is more likely to buy the product as compared to the customers with lower demographic affluent value.
  • All the other variables have a weak correlation with the Target Buy output variable, that means, their impact in determining the output variable is low.
